{"title_page": "The Lone Sailor", "text_new": "{{Italic title|force=true}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| title               = The Lone Sailor\n| image               = Lone Sailor Memorial in DC.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = The original statue in downtown Washington, D.C., located at the US Navy Memorial\n| other_language_1   = \n| other_title_1      = \n| other_language_2   = \n| other_title_2      = \n| artist             = [[Stanley Bleifeld]] \n| year               = 1987\n| type               = [[Bronze]]\n| height_imperial    = \n| width_imperial     = \n| length_imperial    = \n| imperial_unit = ft\n| metric_unit = m\n| city               = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]\n| museum             = [[United States Navy Memorial]]\n| coordinates        = {{Coord|38|53|39|N|77|1|23|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline,title|name= The Lone Sailor, Washington}}\n| owner              = [[National Park Service]]\n}}\n'''''The Lone Sailor''''', a 1987 bronze sculpture, is a tribute to all the personnel of the sea services.  The sculpture was created by [[Stanley Bleifeld]], for the [[United States Navy Memorial]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] \n\n==History==\nRear Admiral William Thompson was the first president and CEO of the Navy Memorial Foundation, which raised the funds to create the Navy Memorial. As a tribute to Thompson's work to bring the memorial to life, sculptor Stanley Bleifeld placed Thompson's initials and last name on the sea bag.<ref name=\"Thompson2010\">{{cite book|last=Thompson|first=William|title=Gumption: My Life \u2013 My Words|year=2010|publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform|isbn=978-1-4538-5357-3|pages=458\u20139}}</ref>  The model for The Lone Sailor was Dan Maloney.<ref>{{cite news |last= Hileman |first= Maria |title= Memorial will showcase Weston artist |newspaper= The Day |location= New London, CT |date= 5 April 1987}}</ref><ref>{{citation |mode= cs1 |type= Correspondence |last= Bleifeld |first= Stanley |title= Letter from sculptor Stanley Bleifeld to William Thompson, President, United States Navy Memorial |date= 9 June 1987}}{{Unreliable source?|reason= Has this been published anywhere?|date=October 2017}}</ref><ref name= \"kid\">{{cite news |title= Here's looking at you kid |last= Moore |first= Kevan |date= 4 September 2012 |newspaper= Kitsap Daily News |url= http://www.kitsapdailynews.com/news/heres-looking-at-you-kid/ |accessdate= 19 October 2017}}</ref> Maloney modeled in 1984 or 1985 when he was a Petty Officer First Class assigned to the submarine USS Alabama.<ref name= \"NSAB\">{{cite press release |last= Blair |first= Bryan |title= NSA Bahrain holds 237th Navy ball |url= http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=70165 |publisher= [[United States Navy]] |agency= Navy News Service |accessdate= 19 October 2017 |page= NNS121016-04 |nopp= yes |date= 16 October 2012}}</ref>  The ''[[Navy Times]]'' published Maloney's first person account of his selection and collaboration with Bleifeld on The Lone Sailor and Liberty Hound statues.<ref>{{cite news |last= Maloney |first= Daniel K. |title= A turn of his collar, and history was made |newspaper= [[Navy Times]] |date= 5 March 2001}}</ref>  The Liberty Hound is located on the Jacksonville, Florida waterfront.  There were several earlier designs for the Lone Sailor but the versions created from those sessions were not approved.<ref>{{cite news |last= McAllister |first= Bill |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1986/12/31/navy-memorial-sculptor-chips-at-washingtons-art-bureaucracy/bb654128-2a12-417e-8fbb-b1301e40de17/?tid=ss_fb-bottom |title= Navy memorial sculptor chips at Washington's art bureaucracy |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |date= 31 December 1986 |accessdate= 15 October 2017}}</ref>  After the failed attempts using Navy Ceremonial Honor Guard models, Bleifeld asked [[New London Submarine Base]] for someone more typical.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.kitsapsun.com/news/2007/dec/27/145lone-sailor-bound-for-bremerton-marina/ |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080308154337/http://www.kitsapsun.com/news/2007/dec/27/145lone-sailor-bound-for-bremerton-marina/ |archive-date= 8 March 2008 |newspaper= [[Kitsap Sun]] |first= Ed |last= Friedrich |title= \u2018Lone Sailor' bound for Bremerton Marina |accessdate= 23 February 2008}}</ref>  \nAs part of the casting process, the bronze for ''The Lone Sailor'' was mixed with artifacts from eight [[U.S. Navy]] ships, provided by the [[Naval Historical Center]].\n\n== Replicas around the United States ==\n[[Image:Lone Sailor watching BB-64.jpg|thumb|''The Lone Sailor'' keeps watch over {{USS|Wisconsin|BB-64|6}}]]\n\nThere are other copies of ''The Lone Sailor'' in memorials around the [[United States]].<ref name= \"StatuesAround\">{{cite web |url= http://www.navymemorial.org/heritage-center/statues-around-country |title= Statues Around the Country |publisher= [[United States Navy Memorial]] |accessdate= 19 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n* [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]], [[USS KIDD Veterans Memorial and Museum]]\n* [[Bremerton, Washington]], Bremerton Marina.{{Coord|47|33|48|N|122|37|25|W|type:landmark_region:US|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Bremerton}}  Dedicated May 23, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |title= The Lone Sailor has come home to Puget Sound |website= www.lonesailor-bremerton.org |url= http://www.lonesailor-bremerton.org/ |accessdate= 10 January 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Burlington, Vermont]], Leahy Center.{{Coord|44|28|33.4|N|73|13|17.7|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Burlington}}\n* [[Charleston, South Carolina]], Charleston Naval Memorial Park.{{Coord|32|51|09|N|79|57|24|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Charleston}}\n* [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]], Esplanade Park overlooking the [[New River (Broward County, Florida)|New River]].{{Coord|26|07|10.8|N|80|08|53.5|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Ft. Lauderdale}}\n* [[Great Lakes, Illinois]], [[Great Lakes Naval Training Center]].{{Coord|42|18|29.0|N|87|50|57.7|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Great Lakes}}\n* [[Jacksonville, Florida]], overlooking the [[St. Johns River]].{{Coord|30|19|12.35|N|81|39|25.64|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Jacksonville}}\n* [[Long Beach, California]], overlooking the [[Pacific Ocean]].{{Coord|33|45|41.7|N|118|09|22.4|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Long Beach}}\n* [[Marin County, California]], above [[Fort Baker]].{{Coord|37|49|57.6|N|122|28|47.8|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, San Francisco}}\n* [[Norfolk, Virginia]], in [[Wisconsin Square]] standing watch over the [[museum ship]] {{USS|Wisconsin|BB-64|6}}.{{Coord|36|50|55.2|N|76|17|39.9|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Norfolk}}\n* [[Orlando, Florida]], in [[Blue Jacket Park]], memorializing the former site of [[Naval Training Center Orlando]].{{Coord|28|34|30.1|N|81|20|16.3|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor Navy Memorial of Central Florida}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://navymemorial.org/lone-sailor-orlando-florida |title= The Lone Sailor \u2013 Orlando, Florida |publisher= [[United States Navy Memorial]] |accessdate= 19 October 2017 }}</ref>\n* [[Pearl Harbor, Hawaii]], at the Pearl Harbor Visitor Center. Dedicated on October 13, 2017.<ref name=\"LSPH\">{{cite news |title= Lone Sailor\u2019s steely gaze now looks out over Pearl Harbor |url= https://www.stripes.com/lone-sailor-s-steely-gaze-now-looks-out-over-pearl-harbor-1.492737 |date= October 15, 2017 |newspaper= [[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]] |accessdate= 19 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Lone Sailor Takes a Stand in Hawaii\">{{Cite web |url=http://navylive.dodlive.mil/2017/10/12/lone-sailor-takes-a-stand-in-hawaii/ |title=Lone Sailor takes a stand in Hawaii |last=Fort |first= Brian |date= 13 July 2017 |website=Navy Live |access-date= 14 October 2017}}</ref>\n* Washington, D.C., in the West Wing of the White House, a 24-inch replica is stationed at the entrance to the White House Mess.{{Citation needed|reason= The following citation documents it's presentation but not it's placement|date=October 2017}} Presented to President Reagan in 1987 by the Navy Memorial Dedication Committee.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://reaganlibrary.archives.gov/archives/audiovisual/WHTV1987.PDF |publisher= [[Ronald Reagan Presidential Library]] |accessdate= 19 October 2017 |page= 267 |title= White House Television Office (WHTV) videotape collection, 1987}}</ref><!-- preceding ref only supports a presentation in the oval office -->\n* [[Waterloo, Iowa]], [[Grout Museum]].<!-- Estimated coordinate --> {{Coord|42|29|35.5|N|92|20|37.0|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Waterloo}} The statue in Waterloo, IA is a tribute to the [[Sullivan Brothers]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Lone Sailor statue unveiled |first= Charles |last= Emerick |date= 3 November 2003 |newspaper= [[The Waterloo-Cedar Falls Courier]] |url= http://wcfcourier.com/news/metro/lone-sailor-statue-unveiled/article_c02cf8f5-3cf2-5ab6-b2b8-a3c2deee1577.html |accessdate= 19 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://navymemorial.org/lone-sailor-waterloo-iowa |title= The Lone Sailor \u2013 Waterloo, Iowa |publisher= [[United States Navy Memorial]] |accessdate= 19 October 2017}}</ref>\n* [[West Haven, Connecticut]], in Old Grove Park.{{Coord|41|15|28.0|N|72|56|54.7|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, West Haven}} The statue in West Haven, CT was donated by residents and Navy veteran, Marty DeGrand.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://navymemorial.org/lone-sailor-west-haven-connecticut |title= The Lone Sailor \u2013 West Haven, Connecticut |publisher= [[United States Navy Memorial]] |accessdate= 19 October 2017}}</ref>\nThere is only one copy of ''The Lone Sailor'' in a memorial outside the [[United States]].\n* [[Utah Beach]], [[Normandy]], on a plaza at the Utah Beach Museum overlooking the Atlantic Ocean from where the U.S. invasion force appeared on D-Day.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.navymemorial.org/lone-sailor-normandy |title= Lone Sailor Statue in Normandy |publisher= [[United States Navy Memorial]] |accessdate= 7 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 6]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category inline}}\n\n{{Public art in Washington, D.C.|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lone Sailor, The}}\n[[Category:1987 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in the United States]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in California]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Florida]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Iowa]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Northwest (Washington, D.C.)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title|force=true}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| title               = The Lone Sailor\n| image               = Lone Sailor Memorial in DC.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = The original statue in downtown Washington, D.C., located at the US Navy Memorial\n| other_language_1   = \n| other_title_1      = \n| other_language_2   = \n| other_title_2      = \n| artist             = [[Stanley Bleifeld]] \n| year               = 1987\n| type               = [[Bronze]]\n| height_imperial    = \n| width_imperial     = \n| length_imperial    = \n| imperial_unit = ft\n| metric_unit = m\n| city               = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]\n| museum             = [[United States Navy Memorial]]\n| coordinates        = {{Coord|38|53|39|N|77|1|23|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline,title|name= The Lone Sailor, Washington}}\n| owner              = [[National Park Service]]\n}}\n'''''The Lone Sailor''''', a 1987 bronze sculpture, is a tribute to all the personnel of the sea services.  The sculpture was created by [[Stanley Bleifeld]], for the [[United States Navy Memorial]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] \n\n==History==\nRear Admiral William Thompson was the first president and CEO of the Navy Memorial Foundation, which raised the funds to create the Navy Memorial. As a tribute to Thompson's work to bring the memorial to life, sculptor Stanley Bleifeld placed Thompson's initials and last name on the sea bag.<ref name=\"Thompson2010\">{{cite book|last=Thompson|first=William|title=Gumption: My Life - My Words|year=2010|publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform|isbn=978-1-4538-5357-3|pages=458\u20139}}</ref>  The model for The Lone Sailor was Dan Maloney.<ref>{{cite news |last= Hileman |first= Maria |title= Memorial will showcase Weston artist |newspaper= The Day |location= New London, CT |date= 5 April 1987}}</ref><ref>{{citation |mode= cs1 |type= Correspondence |last= Bleifeld |first= Stanley |title= Letter from sculptor Stanley Bleifeld to William Thompson, President, United States Navy Memorial |date= 9 June 1987}}{{Unreliable source?|reason= Has this been published anywhere?|date=October 2017}}</ref><ref name= \"kid\">{{cite news |title= Here's looking at you kid |last= Moore |first= Kevan |date= 4 September 2012 |newspaper= Kitsap Daily News |url= http://www.kitsapdailynews.com/news/heres-looking-at-you-kid/ |accessdate= 19 October 2017}}</ref> Maloney modeled in 1984 or 1985 when he was a Petty Officer First Class assigned to the submarine USS Alabama.<ref name= \"NSAB\">{{cite press release |last= Blair |first= Bryan |title= NSA Bahrain holds 237th Navy ball |url= http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=70165 |publisher= [[United States Navy]] |agency= Navy News Service |accessdate= 19 October 2017 |page= NNS121016-04 |nopp= yes |date= 16 October 2012}}</ref>  The ''[[Navy Times]]'' published Maloney's first person account of his selection and collaboration with Bleifeld on The Lone Sailor and Liberty Hound statues.<ref>{{cite news |last= Maloney |first= Daniel K. |title= A turn of his collar, and history was made |newspaper= [[Navy Times]] |date= 5 March 2001}}</ref>  The Liberty Hound is located on the Jacksonville, Florida waterfront.  There were several earlier designs for the Lone Sailor but the versions created from those sessions were not approved.<ref>{{cite news |last= McAllister |first= Bill |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1986/12/31/navy-memorial-sculptor-chips-at-washingtons-art-bureaucracy/bb654128-2a12-417e-8fbb-b1301e40de17/?tid=ss_fb-bottom |title= Navy memorial sculptor chips at Washington's art bureaucracy |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |date= 31 December 1986 |accessdate= 15 October 2017}}</ref>  After the failed attempts using Navy Ceremonial Honor Guard models, Bleifeld asked [[New London Submarine Base]] for someone more typical.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.kitsapsun.com/news/2007/dec/27/145lone-sailor-bound-for-bremerton-marina/ |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080308154337/http://www.kitsapsun.com/news/2007/dec/27/145lone-sailor-bound-for-bremerton-marina/ |archive-date= 8 March 2008 |newspaper= [[Kitsap Sun]] |first= Ed |last= Friedrich |title= \u2018Lone Sailor' bound for Bremerton Marina |accessdate= 23 February 2008}}</ref>  \nAs part of the casting process, the bronze for ''The Lone Sailor'' was mixed with artifacts from eight [[U.S. Navy]] ships, provided by the [[Naval Historical Center]].\n\n== Replicas around the United States ==\n[[Image:Lone Sailor watching BB-64.jpg|thumb|''The Lone Sailor'' keeps watch over {{USS|Wisconsin|BB-64|6}}]]\n\nThere are other copies of ''The Lone Sailor'' in memorials around the [[United States]].<ref name= \"StatuesAround\">{{cite web |url= http://www.navymemorial.org/heritage-center/statues-around-country |title= Statues Around the Country |publisher= [[United States Navy Memorial]] |accessdate= 19 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n* [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]], [[USS KIDD Veterans Memorial and Museum]]\n* [[Bremerton, Washington]], Bremerton Marina.{{Coord|47|33|48|N|122|37|25|W|type:landmark_region:US|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Bremerton}}  Dedicated May 23, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |title= The Lone Sailor has come home to Puget Sound |website= www.lonesailor-bremerton.org |url= http://www.lonesailor-bremerton.org/ |accessdate= 10 January 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Burlington, Vermont]], Leahy Center.{{Coord|44|28|33.4|N|73|13|17.7|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Burlington}}\n* [[Charleston, South Carolina]], Charleston Naval Memorial Park.{{Coord|32|51|09|N|79|57|24|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Charleston}}\n* [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]], Esplanade Park overlooking the [[New River (Broward County, Florida)|New River]].{{Coord|26|07|10.8|N|80|08|53.5|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Ft. Lauderdale}}\n* [[Great Lakes, Illinois]], [[Great Lakes Naval Training Center]].{{Coord|42|18|29.0|N|87|50|57.7|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Great Lakes}}\n* [[Jacksonville, Florida]], overlooking the [[St. Johns River]].{{Coord|30|19|12.35|N|81|39|25.64|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Jacksonville}}\n* [[Long Beach, California]], overlooking the [[Pacific Ocean]].{{Coord|33|45|41.7|N|118|09|22.4|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Long Beach}}\n* [[Marin County, California]], above [[Fort Baker]].{{Coord|37|49|57.6|N|122|28|47.8|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, San Francisco}}\n* [[Norfolk, Virginia]], in [[Wisconsin Square]] standing watch over the [[museum ship]] {{USS|Wisconsin|BB-64|6}}.{{Coord|36|50|55.2|N|76|17|39.9|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor, Norfolk}}\n* [[Orlando, Florida]], in [[Blue Jacket Park]], memorializing the former site of [[Naval Training Center Orlando]].{{Coord|28|34|30.1|N|81|20|16.3|W|type:landmark_region:US_scale:1000|display=inline|name= The Lone Sailor Navy Memorial of Central Florida}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://navymemorial.org/lone-sailor-orlando-florida |title= The Lone Sailor - Orlando, Florida |publisher= [[United States Navy Memorial]] |accessdate= 19 October 2017 }}</ref>\n* [[Pearl Harbor, Hawaii]], at the Pearl Harbor Visitor Center. Dedicated on October 13, 2017.<ref name=\"LSPH\">{{cite news |title= Lone Sailor\u2019s steely gaze now looks out over Pearl Harbor |url= https://www.stripes.com/lone-sailor-s-steely-gaze-now-looks-out-over-pearl-harbor-1.492737 |date= October 15, 2017 |newspaper= [[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]] |accessdate= 19 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Lone Sailor Takes a Stand in Hawaii\">{{Cite web |url=http://navylive.dodlive.mil/2017/10/12/lone-sailor-takes-a-stand-in-hawaii/ |title=Lone Sailor takes a stand in Hawaii |last=Fort |first= Brian |date= 13 July 2017 |website=Navy Live |access-date= 14 October 2017}}</ref>\n* Washington, D.C., in the West Wing of the White House, a 24-inch replica is stationed at the entrance to the White House Mess.{{Citation needed|reason= The following citation documents it's presentation but not it's placement|date=October 2017}} Presented to President Reagan in 1987 by the Navy Memorial Dedication Committee.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://reaganlibrary.archives.gov/archives/audiovisual/WHTV19