on Fox|FOX]] || Eric Clemons & Scott Case || align=\"center\"|40,203* || align=\"center\"|4\u20138\n|- style=\"background:#fdd;\"\n| 14\n| December 1, 1996\n| at [[1996 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]]\n| L 0\u201324 || align=\"center\"|1:00 || [[Bank of America Stadium|Ericsson Stadium]] ||[[NFL on Fox|FOX]] || Thom Brennaman & Ron Pitts || align=\"center\"|57,623 || align=\"center\"|4\u20139\n|- style=\"background:#dfd;\"\n| 15\n| December 8, 1996\n| [[1996 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]]\n| W 10\u201324 || align=\"center\"|1:00 || [[Houlihan's Stadium]] ||[[NFL on Fox|FOX]] || [[Joe Buck]] & [[Bill Maas]] || align=\"center\"|44,723* || align=\"center\"|5\u20139\n|- style=\"background:#fdd;\"\n| 16\n| December 15, 1996\n| at [[1996 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]]\n| L 10\u201321 || align=\"center\"|1:00 || [[Hubert H. Humphrey Metrodome]] ||[[NFL on Fox|FOX]] || Joe Buck & Bill Maas || align=\"center\"|49,302 || align=\"center\"|5\u201310\n|- style=\"background:#dfd;\"\n| 17\n| December 22, 1996\n| [[1996 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]]\n| W 34\u201319 || align=\"center\"|1:00 || [[Houlihan's Stadium]] ||[[NFL on Fox|FOX]] || Thom Brennaman & Ron Pitts || align=\"center\"|51,572* || align=\"center\"|6\u201310\n|}\n\n{{refbegin|1}}\n'''Notes''':\n:{{note label|time|a|a}} All times in [[Eastern Time Zone (North America)|North American Eastern Time]]. (UTC\u20134 and UTC\u20135 during Standard Time)\n{{refend}}\n\n* = blacked out locally\n\n===Standings===\n{{1996 NFC Central standings}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Tampa Bay Buccaneers}}\n{{Tampa Bay Buccaneers seasons}}\n{{1996 NFL season by team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1996 Tampa Bay Buccaneers Season}}\n[[Category:1996 in sports in Florida|Tampa Bay Buccaneers season]]\n[[Category:1996 National Football League season by team|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]\n[[Category:20th century in Tampa, Florida]]\n[[Category:Tampa Bay Buccaneers seasons]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NFL season\n| team = Tampa Bay Buccaneers\n| year = 1996\n| record = 6\u201310\n| division_place = 4th [[NFC North|NFC Central]]\n| coach = [[Tony Dungy]]\n| general manager = [[Rich McKay]]\n| owner = [[Malcolm Glazer]]\n| pro bowlers = {{ Collapsible list\n| title = 3\n| 1 = MLB [[Hardy Nickerson]]\n| 2 = FB [[Mike Alstott]] (alternate)\n| 3 = P [[Tommy Barnhardt]] (alternate)\n}}\n| AP All-pros = FB [[Mike Alstott]], MLB [[Hardy Nickerson]]\n| MVP = MLB [[Hardy Nickerson]]\n| ROY =\n| stadium = [[Houlihan's Stadium]]\n| playoffs = ''Did not qualify''\n| uniform =\n| shortnavlink = Buccaneers seasons\n}}\n\n[[File:Mile High Stadium during a Broncos game on September 15, 1996.jpg|thumb|270px|Tampa Bay kicks off while visiting the [[1996 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] at [[Mile High Stadium]], September 15, 1996]]\n\nThe '''1996 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season''' was the team's 21st in the [[National Football League]].\n\nThe season began with the team trying to improve on a 7\u20139 season in [[1995 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|1995]]. It was the first season for first-time head coach [[Tony Dungy]].\n\nThe 1996 Buccaneers season would be a turning point for the franchise, as the team began to acquire the personnel that would lead it into its most successful era.\n\nThe 1996 season also marked the debut year the team wore stitched up authentic name and numbers on jersey and the final year the Buccaneers wore their trademark orange and white uniforms.\n\n==Offseason==\nPrior to the season the Buccaneers were still unsure if the team would remain in [[Tampa Bay]] or if it would be moved by new ownership family led by [[Malcolm Glazer]] and sons, either to [[Cleveland]],<ref>\"NFL teams shift into move groove: Owners to vote Feb. 8\u20139 on Browns\"; in ''[[The Washington Times]]''; January 19, 1996; p.</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1996/01/18/sports/pro-football-vote-is-delayed-on-browns-relocation.html \u201cPro Football: Vote Is Delayed on Browns\u2019 Relocation\u201d]; in ''[[The New York Times]]''; January 18, 1996</ref> Los Angeles,<ref>\"NFL's Games of Musical Chairs Making Football Fans Fell Dizzy\"; in ''[[Ocala Star-Banner]]'', July 1, 1995; p. 1D</ref><ref>\"NFL Owners Spared Tough Agenda Today\"; in ''[[Charlotte Observer]]''; May 21, 1996</ref> or the nearby city of [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]].<ref>\"No. 1 NFL Rule on Relocation Is That There Are No Rules\"; in ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]''; November 12, 1995; p. 03F</ref> Eventually, the team's future was determined by a local referendum, which approved funding for a new stadium for [[1998 NFL season|the 1998 season]].\n\nRule changes earlier in the decade brought about a salary cap, and a minimum spending cap forced Bucs to spend more on players. With the new ownership, tax disclosures showed the old Culverhouse regime was running a \"for-profit\" business in which players who were getting good were released before their contracts could get big, all the while claiming poor and trying to get some home games played in Orlando.\n\n===NFL Draft===\nPrior to the 1996 season the team drafted fullback [[Mike Alstott]], who became one of the most popular players in the teams history, as well as defensive back [[Donnie Abraham]]. Although Alstott would become one of the Buccaneers\u2019 most popular players of all time, the organization did not target him in the draft: the team had originally wanted tailback [[Leeland McElroy]], who would be taken before the Bucs drafted.\n\n{|\n|-\n|style=\"background:#fc0; border:1px solid #aaaaaa; width:2em;\"|\n|= [[Pro Bowl]]er <ref name=\"Pro Bowler note\">Players are identified as a Pro Bowler if they were selected for the Pro-Bowl at any time in their career.</ref>\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable sortable\" style=\"width: 100%\"\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#de6108; color:#fff; border:2px solid #b20032;\"\n|style=\"border: 2px solid #b20032;\"| '''Pick''' ||style=\"border: 2px solid #b20032;\"| '''Round''' ||style=\"border: 2px solid #b20032;\"| '''Player''' ||style=\"border: 2px solid #b20032;\"| '''Position''' ||style=\"border: 2px solid #b20032;\"| '''School'''\n|-\n|align=center|12||1||[[Regan Upshaw]]||Defensive End||[[California Golden Bears football|California]]\n|-\n|align=center|22||1||[[Marcus Jones (athlete)|Marcus Jones]]||Defensive End||[[North Carolina Tarheels football|North Carolina]]\n|-\n|align=center|35||2|| style=\"background:#fc0;\"|[[Mike Alstott]]||Fullback||[[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]]\n|-\n|align=center|71||3|| style=\"background:#fc0;\"|[[Donnie Abraham]]||Defensive Back||[[East Tennessee State University|ETSU]]\n|-\n|align=center|96||4||[[Jason Odom]]||Offensive Tackle||[[Florida Gators football|Florida]]\n|-\n|align=center|104||4||Eric Austin||Defensive Back||[[Jackson State Tigers#Football|Jackson State]]\n|-\n|align=center|140||5||[[Jason Maniecki]]||Defensive Tackle||[[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin]]\n|-\n|align=center|180||6||Nilo Silvan||Wide Receiver||[[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]]\n|-\n|align=center|221||7||[[Reggie Rusk]]||Defensive Back||[[Kentucky Wildcats football|Kentucky]]\n|}\n\n===Undrafted free agents===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ 1996 Undrafted Free Agents of note\n!Player\n!Position\n!College\n|-\n|[[Scott Milanovich]]\n|Quarterback\n|[[Maryland Terrapins football|Maryland]]\n|}\n\n==Season Summary==\nDespite having been 7\u20137 toward the end of 1995, the 1996 team went 0\u20135 before getting their first win over Tony Dungy's former team, [[1996 Minnesota Vikings season|the Minnesota Vikings]]. The 24\u201313 win over Minnesota started another streak few noted at the time, in which the team held opponents to 13 points or less in four consecutive games. Despite this, [[1996 Oakland Raiders season|the Oakland Raiders]] came to Tampa Bay in Week Eleven facing a 1\u20138 Buccaneers team. Tampa Bay defeated Oakland 20\u201317 in overtime, which was the first of five wins over the next seven games.\n\nThe following week, Tampa Bay traveled to the west coast, where they historically had trouble winning. Playing an interconference game at [[1996 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego]], Tampa Bay quickly found themselves down 14\u20130. The morning of the game, [[Warren Sapp]] and [[Derrick Brooks]] were in their hotel room watching [[ESPN]]'s ''[[Sunday NFL Countdown]]''. [[Chris Berman]] referred to the game as the \"Superchargers\" versus the \"Yucs\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.dailypress.com/2004-03-22/sports/0403220144_1_mike-dupue-sapp-and-linebacker-tampa-bay-buccaneers-history |title=Sapp Earned Tampa Fans' Shrugs|publisher=Daily Press|first=Mike|last=Bianchi|date=2004-03-22|accessdate=2013-08-21}}</ref><ref>\"Relentless: the Road to Canton \u2013 Warren Sapp\": NFL Network</ref> \u2013 a derogatory nickname that had stemmed from the Bucs many years of futility. Sapp and Brooks finally took exception to the ridicule they were being subjected to. Tampa Bay would rally in the game with a 25\u20133 run and won by the score of 25\u201317. Tampa Bay would win two of the next three, including an emotional win over [[1996 Chicago Bears season|Chicago]] 34\u201319 in which the Bucs returned a punt for a touchdown.\n\nMany fans took encouragement from the team going 5\u20132 in the final seven games, as well as the emergence of defensive tackle [[Warren Sapp]] who had nine sacks on the season, linebacker [[Derrick Brooks]], and fullback [[Mike Alstott]], who along with safety [[John Lynch (American football)|John Lynch]] and linebacker [[Hardy Nickerson]], were forming the core of what would prove to be a dominant defense.\n\nThe offense struggled all season, and was not helped by an ill-advised holdout by running back [[Errict Rhett]], who would have far fewer carries the following year.<ref>The bulk of Tampa Bay's carries in 1997 would be handled by Mike Alstott and [[Warrick Dunn]].</ref><ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/R/RhetEr00.htm Pro Football Reference.com: Errict Rhett] Rhett would have only 31 carries for 96 yards for Tampa in 1997.</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n\n===Staff===\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" style=\"background:#ff7900; color:#fff; border:2px solid #c60c30; text-align:center;\"|'''1996 Tampa Bay Buccaneers staff'''\n|-\n|  style=\"font-size:95%; vertical-align:top;\"|\n'''Front Office'''\n* Owner/President \u2013 [[Malcolm Glazer]]\n* General Manager \u2013 [[Rich McKay]]\n* Director of Player Personnel \u2013 [[Jerry Angelo]]\n* Director of College Scouting \u2013 [[Tim Ruskell]]\n\n'''Head Coaches'''\n* Head Coach \u2013 [[Tony Dungy]]\n* Assistant Head Coach/Defensive Backs \u2013 [[Herman Edwards]]\n\n'''Offensive Coaches'''\n\n* Offensive Coordinator \u2013 [[Mike Shula]]\n* Running Backs \u2013 [[Tony Nathan]]\n* Wide Receivers \u2013 Charlie Williams\n* Tight Ends \u2013 [[Clyde Christensen]]\n* Offensive Line \u2013 [[Chris Foerster]]\n* Offensive Assistant \u2013 [[Ricky Porter]]\n|width=\"35\"|&nbsp;\n|valign=\"top\"|\n|  style=\"font-size:95%; vertical-align:top;\"|\n'''Defensive Coaches'''\n* Defensive Coordinator \u2013 [[Monte Kiffin]]\n* Defensive Line \u2013 [[Rod Marinelli]]\n* Linebackers \u2013 [[Lovie Smith]]\n* Defensive Assistant \u2013 [[Kevin O'Dea]]\n\n'''Special Teams Coaches'''\n* Special Teams \u2013 Joe Marciano\n\n'''Strength and Conditioning'''\n* Strength and Conditioning \u2013 Mark Asanovich\n* Strength and Conditioning Assistant \u2013 Aaron Komarek\n|}\n\n<ref>{{cite book |title=2009 Tampa Bay Buccaneers Media Guide |pages=44\u201346 |url=http://www.buccaneers.com/team/mediaguide.aspx |accessdate=2009-11-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100315173010/http://www.buccaneers.com/team/mediaguide.aspx |archive-date=2010-03-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Roster===\n{{NFL final roster\n| year     = 1996\n| team     = Tampa Bay Buccaneers\n| prefix   = \n| active   = \n| inactive 